Both outputs are written and `transcript.json` validates against the schema (13 iterations, 25 hypotheses, 24 analyses).

**Key finding:** A clean 3-way symmetric interaction among three binary features (`feature_001`, `feature_021`, `feature_014`) defines a high-response subgroup (63%) that is nearly abolished by either of two spoiler markers (`feature_026`, `feature_009`). The complete refined subgroup definition

  `feature_001=1 ∧ feature_021=1 ∧ feature_014=1 ∧ feature_026=0 ∧ feature_009=0`

gives 78.6% response (n=1,790) versus 16.5% in the remaining 48,210 patients (risk diff +62.1pp; adjusted OR 21.4 in a model with all 35 features; LRT and chi-square p-values ≈ 0). The effect persists at every level of the dominant prognostic ordinal `feature_004`, and a greedy recursive subgroup search independently rediscovers the same definition. Spoilers do **not** operate in two-of-three subgroups, so their effect is interaction-specific rather than general.
